“When I’m watching it, it almost feels like that’s not me pulling off some of those shots.”

British teenager Emma Raducanu told BBC Breakfast about the "whirlwind" experience of winning the US Open.

The 18-year-old created history by becoming the first British woman in 44 years to win a Grand Slam singles title.

#EmmaRaducanu #USOpen #BBCNews

node.title: Emma Raducanu: ‘US Open win is still sinking in’

"This website was essentially placing a bounty on the heads of women seeking abortions in Texas."

When the strictest abortion law in the US went into effect in Texas, teenagers took matters into their own hands. 

They took to social media to ask people to clog an anti-abortion website with fake tips about offenders.

They managed to bring the site down temporarily, but now the anti-abortion webpage, run by Texas Right to Life, is facing other challenges.

#TikTok #Texas #US #Politics #BBCNews

node.title: How TikTokers took down a Texas anti-abortion site

A doctor combatting myths about the Covid vaccine on TikTok is calling for trainee medics to be given social media lessons within their degrees.

Dr Bnar Talabani is the only doctor from Wales on Team Halo, a UN-backed group of doctors and scientists using social media to dispel vaccine misinformation.

But the former refugee and co-founder of Muslim Doctors Cymru has been labelled "Dr Death" by trolls.

#Coronavirus #TikTok #BBCNews

node.title: TikTok doctor wants social media help for trainees

Since the start of the pandemic, there’s been an increase in the production and smuggling of fake medicines around the world.

Authorities are cracking down on this type of crime and we were given exclusive access to a global operation led by World Customs in Benin in West Africa. 

The market for fake drugs is worth around $200bn worldwide every year. 

Since the operation began World Customs say it has seized more than 307 million illegal medicine items. 99.5% of them were discovered in West and Central Africa.

#Benin #BBCNews

node.title: On the trail of fake drug smugglers

“I blame Larry Nasser, and I also blame an entire system that enabled and perpetrated his abuse.”

Elite US athlete Simone Biles has testified before the US Senate about abuse she suffered at the hands of the disgraced former team doctor.

"How much is a little girl worth?" asked Ms Biles, the most decorated Olympic gymnast of all-time.

Former teammates Aly Raisman and McKayla Maroney also appeared before the committee, along with FBI Director Christopher Wray.

The committee is examining shortcomings in the FBI's investigation into Nassar, who was convicted of sexually abusing girls. A report found numerous missteps and cover-ups by FBI agents, which allowed Nassar's abuse to continue for months after the case was first opened.

Tap the link in our bio to find out what the FBI said at the hearing.

#SimoneBiles #BBCNews

node.title: Olympic gymnasts give powerful testimony about abuse

As governments such as the UK transition to ‘zero carbon’, countries will see the formation of new industries and ‘green’ jobs which didn’t exist a generation ago.

This transition will be a key issue at the COP26 climate talks in Glasgow in November.

Beth, 21, is a research assistant at a vertical farm which uses renewable energy to grow crops which are then sold locally.

Bridie, 23, used to work in hospitality but is now retraining as an apprentice offshore wind turbine technician.

#ClimateChange #COP26 #BBCNews

node.title: Are these the green jobs of the future?

Migrants seeking asylum in the US are pictured in the Rio Grande near the International Bridge between Mexico and the United States, as they wait to be processed.

Around 10,000 have gathered in the area in recent days, leading to a growing humanitarian crisis.

The mostly Haitian migrants are sleeping under the bridge in squalid conditions.

A temporary camp there has few basic services, and migrants waiting in temperatures of 37C (99F) are reportedly going back to Mexico to get supplies.

Tap the link in our bio to read more about the situation on the border. 

(📷 Reuters)

#Mexico #Haiti #US #Migration #BBCNews

Aimee Jan has scooped the Ocean Photographer of the Year award for capturing an image of an endangered green sea turtle surrounded by fish in in Western Australia.

The competition aims to shine a light on the beauty of the sea and the threats it faces.

Second place went to Henley Spiers, for a photo of diving gannets off the Shetland Islands, Scotland.

A striking image of a seahorse carrying a face mask got Nicholas Samaras a nomination in the Conservation Photography category.

Renee Capozzola won the Female Fifty Fathoms Award for her work, including an image of a  blacktip reef shark in French Polynesia. Phil de Glanville took the Community Choice Award for an image of a surfer in Western Australia.

Tap the link in our bio to see more images and learn more about the competition.

(📷 Nicholas Samaras, Aimee Jan, Henley Spiers, Renee Capozzola, Phil de Glanville / Ocean Photography Awards)

node.text:
Sir Clive Sinclair, inventor of the pocket calculator and one of Britain's most prolific innovators, has died.

The self-taught gadgeteer, knighted in 1983, designed products like the miniature TV and small personal computers.

He poured time and money into developing an electric vehicle, the Sinclair C5, which failed to take-off due to mixed reviews and poor performance, but he remained positive.

"The idea that an inventor can come up with some brilliant idea and somebody else will make it all happen is nonsense," he once said.

"Either you do it yourself or it ain't going to happen."

Tap the link in our bio to read more about his incredible life.

(📷 Getty Images)

North Korea says this is its new train-launched missile system.
 
Pictures from state media claim to show it carrying out a ballistic missile test.
 
The country says the missiles flew around 500 miles (800 km) at targets in the sea off the country's east coast.
 
UN resolutions ban North Korea from carrying out tests with ballistic missiles - which can carry either nuclear or conventional warheads - in efforts to curb the country's nuclear programme.
 
Tap the link in our bio to read the full story.

node.text:
A previously unseen Vincent Van Gogh drawing has been discovered, a museum dedicated to the artist has confirmed. 🖼️
 
Study for Worn Out showing an exhausted old man was drawn early in the artist's career in 1882, the Van Gogh Museum said.
 
Tap the link in our bio to find out more about the sketch which has been been sitting in a Dutch family's private collection for more than a century.
 
It went on display at the museum in Amsterdam for the first time on Thursday.
 
The public will be able to see it until 2 January, before it is returned to the private collection.

(📷 Reuters)

#VanGogh #Art #BBCNews

These amazing images are all winners or runners up at this year’s Mangrove Photography Awards. 📸 🌱

The competition aims to show the relationships between wildlife, coastal communities and mangrove forests, as well as the fragility of these unique ecosystems, both above and below the waterline.

There were 1,300 entries from 65 countries, with Musfiqur Rahman named overall winner for his photograph of a wild honey gatherer subduing giant honeybees with smoke, in Bangladesh.

Tap the link in our bio to see more beautiful shots.
